

# Matchthehatch.app Product Overview

# Product Vision

The Matchthehatch.app is geared towards freshwater enthusiasts (e.g., fly fishing anglers), naturalists, conservationists, environmentalists, and organizations that serve them (e.g., retailers, non-profits, associations, government, etc).  The heart of the product is its ability to count and classify aquatic insects.  While there are several Bug ID applications on the market today, most are geared towards terrestrial insects or “Order”-level classification only.  

|  | Mayfly | Caddisfly | Stonefly |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Adult form** | ![][image1] | ![][image2] | ![][image3] |
| **Larval form** | ![][image4] | ![][image5] | ![][image6] |

Aquatic insects are critical players in ecosystems and food webs within and surrounding freshwater rivers, lakes, and streams.  They are the primary source of food for most freshwater fish and many birds.  The diversity of aquatic insects is used by scientists and community organizations like the [Deschutes River Alliance](https://deschutesriveralliance.org/aquatic-insect-survey-app-1) to monitor water quality.  

Many fly fishing anglers rely on knowledge of aquatic insects and their life cycles to catch fish.  The phrase “Match the Hatch” comes from the fly fishing vernacular meaning “know what aquatic insects are in, on, or near the water so you can choose the right artificial fly to catch fish”.

The Matchthehatch.app serves three key needs at Synaptiq: 

1. To eat its own dogfood (or in this case “fish food”);   
2. To grow its business; and   
3. To help solve the world’s most important challenges. 

By creating our own real-life implementation of a novel machine vision solution we put ourselves in our customer’s shoes.  This allows us to better understand “what it takes” from a customer perspective.  It will help us empathize and serve our customers better.  It also provides us an app to actually use when we venture to freshwater locations\!

Since we will own the model and implementation, we have many options on how to leverage it to help grow our business including:

1. Writing stories about our experience building it and sharing these stories  
   publicly to demonstrate our thought leadership attracting interest in our business   
2. Demonstrating the app and it’s moving parts in detail as part of our sales conversations with more technical buyers  
3. Integrating it into existing stories and events (e.g., “How much data do we need?”)    
4. Using it as a fun business development tool when meeting partners, customers, etc.  
5. Launching it as a formal product and monetizing it

Freshwater is critical to most living organism’s survival on this planet. We are struggling to keep this invaluable resource intact for future generations, and we have an unequivocal responsibility to do so given our human-driven impacts.  There are massive water changes happening all around us:  

* Warming from climate change  
* [Acid rain impacts](https://sciencing.com/united-states-affected-acid-rain-4965252.html) on the east coast,   
* [Mine pollution in the rockies](https://www.safewater.org/fact-sheets-1/2017/1/23/miningandwaterpollution),   
* [Ice caps melting](https://www.worldwildlife.org/pages/six-ways-loss-of-arctic-ice-impacts-everyone),   
* Upcoming [dam removals](https://www.safewater.org/fact-sheets-1/2017/1/23/miningandwaterpollution), and   
* The [continued loss of freshwater](https://www.propublica.org/article/colorado-river-water-shortage-jay-famiglietti).

Monitoring water quality is critical to identify and address issues before it's too late. All the scientists in the world can’t possibly monitor the quality of every waterway.  The Matchthehatch.app has a unique opportunity to expand the scale and accuracy of water quality monitoring and education to community members and, perhaps, one day become a marketplace for organizations that serve water enthusiasts.

## Product Phases

While the vision for Matchthehatch.app is extensive, there are three primary stages of the roadmap. 

|  | Q4 2022 | Q1 2023 | Q2 2023 | Q4 2023 | Q1 2024 |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Phase I: Feasibility Study |  |  |  |  |  |
| Phase 2: Minimum Viable Product |  |  |  |  |  |
| Phase 3: Product Launch |  |  |  |  |  |

The Feasibility Study phase will focus on internal use only.  At minimum it will encompass three Orders of aquatic insects:  *Ephemeroptera* (Mayflies), *Trichoptera* (Caddisflies), and *Plecoptera* (Stoneflies).  The goal is to: 

1. [Journal the entire process](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1tTproqBmzs2ZKv6-QC_daPgJUFt1F-TqXXt7d-LU9JA/edit?usp=sharing) from concept, to data collection and labeling, to model training and integration, etc.  
2. Determine the optimal number of insect images and the assigned labels to prepare for the next phase; and  
3. Choose the best platform to build it (e.g., Super Annotate \+ Databricks, Google, or Amazon).  

It will entail an annotation system, hosted model(s) with an API, model-assisted labeling, and a simple low-code mobile app. The final deliverable is an analysis and recommendation report that addresses \#2 and \#3 above plus the complete journal.

The MVP phase will expand upon the Feasibility Study with a richer data set (e.g., down to Family, Genus or Species level) and models, a more consumer-friendly app with login and app tracking, reporting, and a more “production ready” backend.  At the end of this phase, we will distribute a beta app to friends and family crowdsourcing more real-life photos through the app while we improve the accuracy and depth of classification (e.g., Order \-\> Family).

The Product Launch phase (if we make it that far) will incorporate monetization features and scalable distribution strategies. 

Potential monetization features:

* Affiliate sales e.g., buy flies like this from Amazon or the local fly shop  
* Advertisements or paid content from fly shops and guides for locations you’d like to fish  
* Predict when and where the “big hatch” will happen (and book a guide for that time period)  
* Machine-vision enabled mobile water quality assessments for government, non-profits/associations, or environmental services businesses  
* Research data for conservation, environment or academic studies  
* Paid content and insights driven from collected data

The “free version” would be distributed through influencers (e.g., [Beau Beasely](https://www.linkedin.com/in/beaubeasley/)), fly fishing festivals, local fisheries departments and conservation organizations, retail partners, and non-profits like Trout Unlimited, the Nature Conservancy, etc.  And premium features would be sold through the app itself.

# Phase I: Feasibility Study

## Personas & Stakeholders

The primary user of the app is a Fly Fishing Angler.  The typical angler is aware of the common aquatic insects because s/he purchases flies online or at fly shops prior to fishing.  However, common names (e.g., “pale morning dun”) are not the same as scientific names (e.g., *Emphemerella excrucians*). Most anglers are not aquatic entomologists, they rely on their friends or fly fishing guides to recommend what artificial flies they should use to catch fish on a specific location at a specific time.  Many fly anglers are naturalists at heart so they enjoy learning about zoology and ecology as they pertain to catching fish.   
The goal of the fly fishing angler is threefold:  1\) Enjoy nature alone or with friends or family; 2\) Catch fish; 3\) Preserve and protect the water and its fish for future generations.  The first two goals are experience-based and emotionally-driven and hard to measure. The last goal today requires active involvement in organizations like [Trout Unlimited](http://www.tu.org), [Save Our Streams](https://vasos.org/), or their local fisheries department.  These organizations collect water quality and biodiversity data regularly, attempt to remediate issues when identified, and share stories of their successes to raise money for future work. 

The typical tasks of a fly angler are as follows:

1. Determine when and where to go fishing and who to go fishing with  
2. Read or talk to people who have fished that location regularly and ask for equipment advice (e.g., flies to use) and where to go given weather conditions and water levels  
3. Purchase flies before the trip to optimize their likelihood of catching fish  
4. Fish   
5. Share, gloat, etc. about all the fish they caught and the fun they had  
6. Repeat 1 as soon as possible

Fly fishing anglers with a deeper science interest spend time observing their surroundings while fishing.  For example, they turn over rocks and investigate banks and vegetation to see what aquatic insects are present.

The biggest challenge a fly angler has is to catch fish (\#4). Therefore, s/he is very focused on what flies to use and perfecting the technique of casting, presenting flies, and hooking and reeling in fish.  This is driven by the intense satisfaction (dopamine rush) they get when they land a fish (especially a big fish) and, for most, when they can share a picture of it with their friends.

There is nothing more disheartening to a fly fishing angler than learning a water they used to fish [became unfishable](https://www.deschutesriver.org/blog/news/crooked-river-ramps-down-at-historic-records-putting-fish-in-peril/).  While this doesn’t happen too often, when it does, it can make a long-term impact on them, their friends, and their families.  Unfortunately, given expected climate changes and increasing environmental pollution, this may accelerate.

The secondary user of the app is the Aquatic Entomologist. This person is enamored with the natural world around them.  S/he gets a kick out of categorizing bugs into beautiful latin names and teaching others about their incredible life cycles.  The Aquatic Entomologist is a highly analytical person. The Aquatic Entomologist faces several challenges:

1. The sheer volume of aquatic insects to manually classify (there are only so many hours one can lean over into a desktop microscope without suffering severe neck and eye pain)  
2. The amount of time (and physical strain) it takes to collect a representative sample of aquatic insects for each location   
3. The lack of deep data-driven models to understand the dynamics of location-specific ecological changes (this would be a particularly interesting study with the upcoming Klamath river dam removal)

# Use Cases

## Fly Fishing Angler

As a Fly Fishing Angler, I can take a photo of insects from my smartphone and see a count for each insect at the Order level along with the common name, latin name, and artificial flies associated to each 

\[Extra Points\] As a Fly Fishing Angler, I can take a photo of insects from my smartphone and see a count for each insect at the Family/Genus/Species level along with the common name, latin name, and artificial flies associated to each 

## Aquatic Entomologist

As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can upload photos of insects for labeling

As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can review photos for labeling and draw bounding boxes around insects in each photo and label their Order, Sex?, and Stage?

As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can retrain and deploy new/updated model(s)

As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can upload a mapping table of latin names to common names to artificial fly names

As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can view the confidence levels for all machine-driven classifications

As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can view a log of photo to label classifications where the confidence level is below a given threshold

As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can relabel existing photos 

As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can count the number of labeled and unlabeled photos by Order, Sex?, and Stage?

\[Extra Points\] As an Aquatic Entomologist, in each uploaded photo I can draw bounding boxes around insects and label their Family, Genus, or Species

\[Extra Points\] As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can count the number of labeled and unlabeled photos by Family, Genus, or Species

\[Extra Points\] As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can visualize similarities (e.g., clustering) between photos of insects to identify new opportunities for labeling

\[Extra Points\] As an Aquatic Entomologist, I can upload GPS bounding boxes of a particular waters and common aquatic insects found in that location

\[A little out there, but I’ve read that bug density matters for stream health. Is it practical/possible to take a photo of the underside of an entire rock and count bugs?\]

We should consider journaling/checklist of bugs ID’d by someone. I see this in bird ID apps and it’s pretty cool to build your list of bugs you’ve seen/ID’d in the app. It’s both practically useful and a gaming driver. And, like birders, if you happen to encounter rare species having other app users kudo you on it is why some of these folks wake up in the morning.  Future features could have missions/bounties on IDing certain species in certain bodies of water, etc.
